    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "A 57-year-old man with diabetes and chronic hepatitis B presented with epistaxis and symptomatic anaemia. His past medical history was relevant for recurrent presentations with epistaxis resulting in chronic iron deficiency anaemia requiring transfusions. Physical examination reviewed multiple telangiectasias affecting the tongue, lips ( Figure A) , face and scalp, digits and the palmer aspect of the hands ( Figure B ). He also has numerous telangiectasia in the nasal passage. Patient recounted that bleeding can be severe; profuse epistaxis and bleeding from finger tips and scalp with spurting that can reach the ceiling.",
